 uptown, evangelicals stood ready to build meetinghouses. As the city’s financial center emerged and solidified, evangelicals capitalized on the resultant wealth, technology, and resources to expand their missionary and benevolent causes. When they began to feel that the city’s morals had degenerated, evangelicals turned to temperance, Sunday school, prayer meetings, antislavery causes, and urban missions to reform their neighbors. The result of these efforts was Evangelical Gotham—a complicated and contradictory world whose influence spread far beyond the shores of Manhattan. Winner of the 2015 Dixon Ryan Fox Manuscript Prize from the New York State Historical Association  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCity churcheszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy18th century. 0aCity churcheszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aEvangelicalismzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy18th century. 0aEvangelicalismzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  anew york city, religion, religious, evangelicalism, evangelical, christianity, christians, public history, historical, immigration, commerce, real estate, urban spaces, cities, american revolution, civil war, united states of america, usa, meetinghouse, influences, missionary work, morality, morals, sunday school, temperance, anti slavery movements, prayer, 19th century, church, gender, reform.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022638814440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226388281423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226388281/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban